1
00:01:00,100 --> 00:01:02,101
[BANGING]

2
00:01:04,397 --> 00:01:06,105
What the fuck is that?

3
00:01:06,816 --> 00:01:07,983
Jimmy?

4
00:01:08,275 --> 00:01:10,027
-What's up?
-Did I hit something?

5
00:01:10,194 --> 00:01:11,861
What the fuck is that?

6
00:01:12,906 --> 00:01:14,531
Maybe you got a flat?

7
00:01:15,408 --> 00:01:17,658
Wha--? No.

8
00:01:19,287 --> 00:01:21,245
What the fuck?
You better pull over and see.

9
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:28,920
[BANGING]

10
00:01:46,855 --> 00:01:48,106
[STAMMERING]

11
00:01:48,399 --> 00:01:50,651
He's still alive. You fucking piece of shit!

12
00:01:50,819 --> 00:01:53,653
Die, you motherfucker! Look at me!

13
00:02:03,123 --> 00:02:07,084
HENRY: As far back as I can remember,
I always wanted to be a gangster.

14
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:48,082
To me...

15
00:02:48,251 --> 00:02:52,503
...being a gangster was better than
being president of the United States.

16
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:59,343
Even before I first wandered
into the cabstand for an after-school job...

17
00:02:59,512 --> 00:03:01,597
I knew I wanted to be a part of them.

18
00:03:01,764 --> 00:03:04,182
It was there that I knew I belonged.

19
00:03:04,349 --> 00:03:08,853
To me, it meant being somebody
in a neighborhood full of nobodies.

20
00:03:09,021 --> 00:03:12,106
They weren't like anybody else.
They did whatever they wanted.

21
00:03:12,275 --> 00:03:15,860
They double-parked in front of a hydrant,
nobody ever gave them a ticket.

22
00:03:16,028 --> 00:03:18,237
In the summer,
when they played cards all night...

23
00:03:18,406 --> 00:03:20,657
...nobody ever called the cops.

24
00:03:22,284 --> 00:03:24,118
[MEN CHATTERING]

25
00:03:32,836 --> 00:03:34,712
MAN:
Tony Stacks. How are you?

26
00:03:36,007 --> 00:03:37,507
HENRY:
Tuddy Cicero.

27
00:03:37,675 --> 00:03:39,926
Could this be the Canarsie Kid?

28
00:03:40,552 --> 00:03:42,094
-How are you?
-Good.

29
00:03:43,389 --> 00:03:44,555
HENRY:
Tuddy.

30
00:03:45,474 --> 00:03:48,518
Tuddy ran the cabstand
and the Bella Vista Pizzeria...

31
00:03:48,686 --> 00:03:53,314
and other places for his brother, Paul,
who was the boss of the neighborhood.

32
00:03:53,816 --> 00:03:55,817
[LAUGHING]

33
00:03:57,945 --> 00:04:00,239
Paulie might have moved slow...

34
00:04:02,699 --> 00:04:06,662
but it was only because Paulie
didn't have to move for anybody.

35
00:04:11,334 --> 00:04:12,960
-It's your fault.
-You started it.

36
00:04:13,127 --> 00:04:15,169
I started it? It's your fault.

37
00:04:15,337 --> 00:04:17,505
HENRY: At first my parents loved
that I found a job...

38
00:04:17,673 --> 00:04:19,757
across the street from the house.

39
00:04:20,884 --> 00:04:24,637
My father, who was Irish,
was sent to work at the age of 11.

40
00:04:24,930 --> 00:04:26,723
He liked that I got myself a job.

41
00:04:26,891 --> 00:04:30,435
He always used to say
that American kids were spoiled lazy.

42
00:04:32,230 --> 00:04:33,855
-Bye, Dad.
-Bye.

43
00:04:34,356 --> 00:04:35,649
See you, Mikey.

44
00:04:35,817 --> 00:04:37,024
Bye, Henry.

45
00:04:37,192 --> 00:04:39,360
HENRY'S MOTHER:
Henry! Watch how you cross!

46
00:04:39,528 --> 00:04:40,778
Bring back milk!

47
00:04:40,947 --> 00:04:44,074
HENRY: My mother was happy after
she found out that the Ciceros...

48
00:04:44,242 --> 00:04:47,786
came from the same part of Sicily
as she did. To my mother...

49
00:04:47,954 --> 00:04:50,747
that was the answer to all her prayers.

50
00:04:52,457 --> 00:04:54,668
I was the luckiest kid in the world.

51
00:04:54,836 --> 00:04:57,670
I could go anywhere, I could do anything.

52
00:04:57,838 --> 00:05:00,507
I knew everybody,
and everybody knew me.

53
00:05:00,966 --> 00:05:03,718
Wiseguys would pull up
and Tuddy would toss me their keys...

54
00:05:03,886 --> 00:05:05,637
and let me park their Cadillacs.

55
00:05:05,805 --> 00:05:09,391
Here I am, this little kid,
I can't even see over the steering wheel...

56
00:05:09,559 --> 00:05:11,726
and I'm parking Cadillacs.

57
00:05:14,980 --> 00:05:17,106
But it wasn't too long...

58
00:05:17,274 --> 00:05:21,069
before my parents changed
their minds about my job at the cabstand.

59
00:05:21,237 --> 00:05:22,862
For your mother and sister.

60
00:05:23,031 --> 00:05:26,408
HENRY: For them, the cabstand was
supposed to be a part-time job. But for me...

61
00:05:26,576 --> 00:05:28,535
it was definitely full-time.

62
00:05:28,702 --> 00:05:30,620
That's all I wanted to do.

63
00:05:30,788 --> 00:05:34,957
People like my father could never
understand, but I was a part of something.

64
00:05:35,125 --> 00:05:37,918
I belonged. I was treated like a grown-up.

65
00:05:38,754 --> 00:05:40,254
Tell him 519.

66
00:05:40,505 --> 00:05:42,423
HENRY:
Every day I was learning to score.

67
00:05:42,591 --> 00:05:45,093
A dollar here, a dollar there.

68
00:05:45,261 --> 00:05:47,178
I was living in a fantasy.

69
00:05:47,346 --> 00:05:49,389
[MEN CHATTERING]

70
00:05:49,723 --> 00:05:51,266
Did you have a good day at school?

71
00:05:51,433 --> 00:05:53,225
HENRY:
My father was always pissed off.

72
00:05:53,394 --> 00:05:55,519
Pissed that he made such lousy money...

73
00:05:55,687 --> 00:05:58,606
pissed that my kid brother Michael
was in a wheelchair.

74
00:05:58,774 --> 00:06:03,028
He was pissed that there were seven of us
living in such a tiny house.

75
00:06:03,446 --> 00:06:04,904
Tell me about this.

76
00:06:05,572 --> 00:06:07,615
It's a letter from school.

77
00:06:08,117 --> 00:06:10,951
It says you haven't been there in months.

78
00:06:12,204 --> 00:06:13,538
In months!

79
00:06:13,706 --> 00:06:14,872
[HENRY'S MOTHER SCREAMING]

80
00:06:15,040 --> 00:06:16,665
You're a bum!

81
00:06:16,834 --> 00:06:19,086
Want to grow up to be a bum?

82
00:06:20,629 --> 00:06:24,800
HENRY: After a while, he was mostly pissed
because I hung around the cabstand.

83
00:06:24,966 --> 00:06:26,843
He knew what went on at that cabstand.

84
00:06:27,011 --> 00:06:31,639
Every once in a while, I'd have to take
a beating. But by then, I didn't care.

85
00:06:31,973 --> 00:06:33,682
The way I saw it...

86
00:06:34,018 --> 00:06:36,644
everybody takes a beating sometime.

87
00:06:37,939 --> 00:06:41,858
-I can't make any more deliveries.
-What? You'll fuck everything up.

88
00:06:42,026 --> 00:06:43,944
My dad says he'll kill me. Look.

89
00:06:44,112 --> 00:06:45,403
Come on with me.

90
00:06:45,696 --> 00:06:47,613
MAN: Is that him, kid?
HENRY: No.

91
00:06:48,281 --> 00:06:49,990
MAN: How about him?
-No.

92
00:06:51,994 --> 00:06:54,036
-That's the guy.
-Get him.

93
00:06:55,831 --> 00:06:57,165
Excuse me.

94
00:06:58,334 --> 00:07:01,002
-Scumbag.
-Come here, you piece of shit.

95
00:07:08,802 --> 00:07:10,928
-Know this kid?
-Yeah.

96
00:07:11,096 --> 00:07:12,764
TUDDY: Know where he lives?
-Yeah.

97
00:07:12,932 --> 00:07:15,057
TUDDY: You deliver mail to his house?
MAILMAN: Yeah.

98
00:07:15,225 --> 00:07:19,062
TUDDY: From now on, any letter from that
school to his house comes directly here.

99
00:07:19,230 --> 00:07:20,521
-Understand?
MAILMAN: Yeah.

100
00:07:20,689 --> 00:07:23,274
TUDDY: Another letter from that school
goes to that kid's house...

101
00:07:23,442 --> 00:07:25,819
in the fucking oven you'll go, head first.

102
00:07:25,987 --> 00:07:30,281
HENRY: That was it. No more letters from
truant officers. No letters from school.

103
00:07:30,449 --> 00:07:32,533
In fact, no more letters from anybody.

104
00:07:32,701 --> 00:07:36,495
Finally after a few weeks, my mother
went to the post office to complain.

105
00:07:36,831 --> 00:07:38,497
How could I go to school after that...

106
00:07:38,665 --> 00:07:42,793
and pledge allegiance to the flag
and sit through good government bullshit?

107
00:07:45,882 --> 00:07:49,050
Paulie hated phones.
He wouldn't have one in his house.

108
00:07:49,218 --> 00:07:51,887
Mickey called. Want me to call him back?

109
00:07:52,262 --> 00:07:53,889
All right, make the call.

110
00:07:54,055 --> 00:07:57,641
HENRY: He got all his calls second hand.
Then you'd have to call the people back...

111
00:07:57,810 --> 00:07:58,851
from an outside phone.

112
00:07:59,019 --> 00:08:01,480
Got a nickel? Get him on the phone.

113
00:08:02,230 --> 00:08:06,985
HENRY: There were guys, that's all they did
all day, was take care of Paulie's calls.

114
00:08:13,242 --> 00:08:15,576
[CHATTERING]

115
00:08:16,620 --> 00:08:20,915
For a guy who moved all day long,
Paulie didn't talk to six people.

116
00:08:21,082 --> 00:08:24,084
If there was a union problem
or, say, a beef in the numbers...

117
00:08:24,252 --> 00:08:27,755
only the top guys could meet
with Paulie to discuss the problem.

118
00:08:27,923 --> 00:08:31,175
Everything was one-on-one.
Paulie hated conferences.

119
00:08:31,927 --> 00:08:34,386
He didn't want anybody
hearing what he said...

120
00:08:34,554 --> 00:08:37,849
and he didn't want anybody listening
to what he was being told.

121
00:08:38,017 --> 00:08:42,269
Hundreds of guys depended on Paulie,
he got a piece of everything they made.

122
00:08:42,437 --> 00:08:46,774
It was a tribute, like in the old country,
except they were doing it in America.

123
00:08:46,942 --> 00:08:51,403
All they got from Paulie was protection
from other guys looking to rip them off.

124
00:08:51,572 --> 00:08:55,491
That's what it's all about. That's what
the FBI could never understand.

125
00:08:55,951 --> 00:08:58,119
What Paulie and the Organization does...

126
00:08:58,287 --> 00:09:02,206
is offer protection for people
who can't go to the cops. That's it.

127
00:09:02,792 --> 00:09:06,919
That's all it is. They're like
the police department for wiseguys.

128
00:09:07,129 --> 00:09:08,421
[GLASS SHATTERING]

129
00:09:16,721 --> 00:09:20,808
People looked at me differently,
and they knew I was with somebody.

130
00:09:20,976 --> 00:09:25,437
I didn't have to wait in line at the bakery
on Sunday mornings for fresh bread.

131
00:09:25,605 --> 00:09:26,855
The owner knew who I was with...

132
00:09:27,024 --> 00:09:30,402
and he'd come from around the counter.
No matter how many were waiting...

133
00:09:30,570 --> 00:09:32,571
I was taken care of first.

134
00:09:32,822 --> 00:09:35,155
Our neighbors didn't park
in our driveway anymore...

135
00:09:35,323 --> 00:09:38,158
even though we didn't have a car.
At 13...

136
00:09:38,326 --> 00:09:40,995
I was making more money than most
of the grown-ups around.

137
00:09:41,163 --> 00:09:44,290
I had more money than I could spend.
I had it all.

138
00:09:54,427 --> 00:09:59,096
One day, some neighborhood kids carried
my mother's groceries all the way home.

139
00:09:59,264 --> 00:10:00,682
You know why?

140
00:10:01,517 --> 00:10:03,350
It was out of respect.

141
00:10:05,104 --> 00:10:07,187
Hi, Mom, what do you think?

142
00:10:08,816 --> 00:10:11,525
-Look at my shoes, aren't they great?
-My God.

143
00:10:12,068 --> 00:10:13,695
You look like a gangster.

144
00:10:13,863 --> 00:10:15,529
They shot me. Help!

145
00:10:15,947 --> 00:10:17,990
[MAN YELLING]

146
00:10:18,158 --> 00:10:19,951
TUDDY:
Henry, shut the door.

147
00:10:20,952 --> 00:10:24,246
HENRY: That was the first time
I had ever seen anyone shot.

148
00:10:25,041 --> 00:10:27,458
Can't have that in here. Jesus Christ!

149
00:10:27,626 --> 00:10:29,251
I can't have that in this joint.

150
00:10:29,419 --> 00:10:31,211
HENRY:
I remember feeling bad about the guy...

151
00:10:31,379 --> 00:10:34,506
but I also remember feeling
that maybe Tuddy was right.

152
00:10:34,759 --> 00:10:37,384
I knew Paulie didn't want
anybody dying in the building.

153
00:10:37,552 --> 00:10:41,389
You're a real jerk. You wasted
eight fucking aprons on this guy.

154
00:10:41,557 --> 00:10:44,725
What the hell's wrong with you?
I got to toughen this kid up.

155
00:11:04,496 --> 00:11:06,413
HENRY:
It was a glorious time.

156
00:11:07,332 --> 00:11:09,918
And wiseguys were all over the place.

157
00:11:10,878 --> 00:11:13,837
It was before Apalachin
and before Crazy Joe...

158
00:11:14,005 --> 00:11:16,924
decided to take on a boss and start a war.

159
00:11:17,592 --> 00:11:19,635
It was when I met the world.

160
00:11:19,803 --> 00:11:22,514
And it was when I first met
Jimmy Conway.

161
00:11:23,974 --> 00:11:27,143
He couldn't have been more than 28 or 29
at the time...

162
00:11:27,311 --> 00:11:29,229
but he was already a legend.

163
00:11:29,397 --> 00:11:33,399
He'd walk in the door and everybody
who worked the room just went wild.

164
00:11:33,567 --> 00:11:36,152
He'd give the doorman $100
just for opening the door.

165
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:40,240
He'd give hundreds to the dealers
and the guys who ran the games.

166
00:11:40,408 --> 00:11:43,368
The bartender got $100
just for keeping the ice cubes cold.

167
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:46,620
The Irishman is here
to take all you guineas' money.

168
00:11:49,834 --> 00:11:52,585
-Want a drink?
-Give me a 7 and 7.

169
00:11:59,719 --> 00:12:03,096
-I'd like you to meet the kid Henry.
-How you doing?

170
00:12:05,474 --> 00:12:08,183
-Thank you.
-Keep them coming.

171
00:12:08,351 --> 00:12:11,354
HENRY: Jimmy was one of the most
feared guys in the city.

172
00:12:11,522 --> 00:12:13,148
He was first locked up at 11...

173
00:12:13,315 --> 00:12:16,400
and he was doing hits
for mob bosses when he was 16.

174
00:12:16,568 --> 00:12:19,361
See, hits never bothered Jimmy.
It was business.

175
00:12:19,822 --> 00:12:21,905
But what Jimmy really loved to do...

176
00:12:22,073 --> 00:12:24,116
what he really loved to do was steal.

177
00:12:24,284 --> 00:12:26,452
He actually enjoyed it.

178
00:12:26,620 --> 00:12:30,539
Jimmy was the kind of guy who rooted
for the bad guys in the movies.

179
00:12:31,250 --> 00:12:33,000
Give me your wallet.

180
00:12:36,004 --> 00:12:39,173
You might know who we are,
but we know who you are. Understand?

181
00:12:39,341 --> 00:12:41,717
HENRY: He was one of
the city's biggest hijackers...

182
00:12:41,885 --> 00:12:45,346
of booze, cigarettes, razor blades,
shrimp and lobsters.

183
00:12:45,514 --> 00:12:48,640
Shrimp and lobsters were best.
They went really fast.

184
00:12:48,808 --> 00:12:52,604
Almost all of them were gimmies.
They just gave it up, no problem.

185
00:12:52,772 --> 00:12:54,438
They called him Jimmy the Gent.

186
00:12:54,606 --> 00:12:55,731
Help the lady.

187
00:12:55,899 --> 00:12:58,192
HENRY: Drivers loved him.
They used to tip him off...

188
00:12:58,360 --> 00:13:01,696
about the really good loads.
Of course, everybody got a piece.

189
00:13:01,864 --> 00:13:03,947
WOMAN:
Thanks, I'll be back for the rest later.

190
00:13:04,115 --> 00:13:05,533
JIMMY:
Okay, see you later.

191
00:13:08,037 --> 00:13:09,703
Henry, come here.

192
00:13:10,623 --> 00:13:12,664
-Say hello to Tommy.
-How're you doing, Henry?

193
00:13:12,832 --> 00:13:14,833
You're gonna be working together, okay?

194
00:13:15,001 --> 00:13:16,711
Help him. Go ahead.

195
00:13:17,086 --> 00:13:19,379
Jimmy, you got anything good?

196
00:13:19,548 --> 00:13:23,592
HENRY: And when the cops assigned a
whole army to stop Jimmy, what did he do?

197
00:13:23,760 --> 00:13:24,802
JIMMY:
How're you doing?

198
00:13:24,970 --> 00:13:26,678
HENRY:
He made them partners.

199
00:13:26,846 --> 00:13:28,472
I'd complain, but who'd listen?

200
00:13:28,807 --> 00:13:30,432
MAN 1: One Pall Mall.
HENRY: There you go.

201
00:13:30,600 --> 00:13:32,684
-What do you need?
MAN 2: Two Luckies.

202
00:13:32,852 --> 00:13:34,729
TOMMY: Here you go, Henry.
-Thanks a lot.

203
00:13:34,897 --> 00:13:35,938
What do you need?

204
00:13:36,105 --> 00:13:38,732
-One Pall Mall.
-One Pall Mall, here you go.

205
00:13:38,900 --> 00:13:40,567
-What are you doing?
-It's all right.

206
00:13:40,735 --> 00:13:43,738
-You have permission from your mother?
-How many cartons you need?

207
00:13:43,905 --> 00:13:46,950
-Where'd you get the cigarettes?
-Get him out of here.

208
00:13:47,116 --> 00:13:48,743
-It's okay.
-It's not okay.

209
00:13:48,911 --> 00:13:52,288
HENRY: You don't understand.
MAN: You don't understand. Store's closed.

210
00:13:57,126 --> 00:13:58,961
-Henry got pinched.
-Where?

211
00:13:59,129 --> 00:14:00,797
By the factory, selling cigarettes.

212
00:14:00,965 --> 00:14:04,926
MAN: Henry Hill. The People of
the State of New York vs. Henry Hill.

213
00:14:05,219 --> 00:14:08,011
Docket number 704162.

214
00:14:09,097 --> 00:14:11,390
Uh, yes, sir. That's me.

215
00:14:14,186 --> 00:14:16,937
Just stand there. Now stay there.

216
00:14:23,361 --> 00:14:25,113
Counselor, proceed.

217
00:14:28,116 --> 00:14:29,741
Congratulations.

218
00:14:30,034 --> 00:14:31,870
Here's your graduation present.

219
00:14:32,037 --> 00:14:35,081
-What for? I got pinched.
-Everyone does, but you did it right.

220
00:14:35,249 --> 00:14:37,292
You told them nothing,
and they got nothing.

221
00:14:37,459 --> 00:14:40,628
-I thought you'd be mad.
-I'm not mad, I'm proud of you.

222
00:14:40,796 --> 00:14:45,091
You took your first pinch like a man
and learned the two greatest things in life.

223
00:14:45,259 --> 00:14:47,594
-What?
-Look at me.

224
00:14:48,303 --> 00:14:50,429
Never rat on your friends...

225
00:14:50,597 --> 00:14:52,932
and always keep your mouth shut.

226
00:14:56,019 --> 00:14:57,477
MAN:
Here he is.

227
00:14:57,937 --> 00:14:59,813
You broke your cherry.

228
00:14:59,981 --> 00:15:01,816
[CHEERING]

229
00:15:06,864 --> 00:15:08,489
MAN:
Congratulations!

230
00:15:10,326 --> 00:15:12,326
[INDECIPHERABLE CHATTER]

231
00:15:43,192 --> 00:15:46,443
HENRY: By the time I grew up,
there was $30 billion a year in cargo...

232
00:15:46,611 --> 00:15:48,363
moving through Idlewild Airport...

233
00:15:48,529 --> 00:15:51,615
and believe me,
we tried to steal every bit of it.

234
00:15:52,033 --> 00:15:54,534
See, you gotta understand,
we grew up near the airport.

235
00:15:54,702 --> 00:15:56,203
It belonged to Paulie.

236
00:15:56,371 --> 00:15:59,039
We had friends and relatives
